Prostomium low, blunt cone, directed ventrally. In ventral view, a deep longitudinal furrow along prostomium (
Fig. 11A
). Peristomium barely exposed, forming an inverted T. Anterior thoracic region with first 7 chaetigers. Segments progressively longer; first three barely annulated, bent ventrally, following ones with fine annulations. Posterior thorax with chaetigers 8–17, segment length progressively reduced in chaetigers 8–10 and then of about same length but poorly defined. Segments homogeneously annulated. Third region with chaetigers 19–24, segments twice as long as wide, with integument barely annulated, almost smooth, transparent, parapodial lobes depressed. Fourth region with chaetigers 23–36, homogeneously short, with integument annulated and parapodial lobes well developed.

Parapodia biramous, displaced dorsally throughout (
Fig. 10D
). Interramal papillae capitate, peduncle as long as distal, globose region (
Figs 11B
, 
12C
). Parapodial development varies along body. Chaetigers 1–4 with chaetal lobes flat, not projected nor glandular. Chaetigers 5–18 with chaetal lobes long, fusiform, then wider, crescent shaped up to chaetiger 14, where they become shorter, rounded (
Fig. 11B, C
). Abdomen with chaetigers 19–24 with chaetal lobes barely visible, not projected or glandular (
Fig. 11D, E
); chaetigers 25–35 with parapodial lobes ovoid, projected and glandular.
